ws.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eIn Zubko-Valva’s motion filed Saturday, she called the county’s $3 million offer “humiliating.” She argued that\u0026nbsp;after she would have paid her lawyer, Jon Norinsberg of Manhattan,\u0026nbsp;his fees, the settlement would “leave almost nothing” for her two surviving children.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003e“Was this your grand plan from the beginning of this case to ensure that my children, who suffered such tremendous and horrific abuse that resulted in my son Tommy’s brutal murder, would be left with nothing?” Zubko-Valva asked her attorney in a July email. “That’s unspeakable and shameful.”\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eNorinsberg said a “complete breakdown” occurred this year over “sharp disagreements” between him and Zubko-Valva over “case strategy, the scope of discovery and the best way to move forward in this case.”\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eU.S. Magistrate Judge Arlene Lindsay on Thursday stayed the case until Jan. 14\u0026nbsp;to give Zubko-Valva two months to\u0026nbsp;find a new lawyer.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003e“It is well-settled that a lawyer may seek to withdraw when the client renders it unreasonably difficult for the lawyer to carry out [such] employment effectively,” Lindsay wrote in her decision. “Where a client’s relationship with its attorney has deteriorated to such an extent that continued representation would be inappropriate the motion [to withdraw as attorney] should be granted.”\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003ca class=\"p-smartembed\" data-attr-caption=\"Justyna Zubko-Valva, mother of Thomas Valva, speaks outside Suffolk County Court in Riverhead in 2020.\n\" data-attr-credit=\"\" data-attr-f=\"3x2\" data-attr-has-caption=\"true\" data-attr-has-credit=\"true\" data-attr-q=\"0.3\" data-attr-w=\"400\" data-onecms-id=\"contentid/f318e1a2-6cc7-43b7-80b1-9fac0177c727\" data-onecms-type=\"image\" href=\"javascript:window.parent.actionEventData({$contentId:'contentid/f318e1a2-6cc7-43b7-80b1-9fac0177c727', $actio